@node introduction "cha_filter.guide/Introduction"

cha_filter is a plugin to add proper filtering capabilities
to OctaMED SoundStudio / nsm.

I got fed up with getting rubbish results from OSS's filter
and boost.  cha_filter uses pro-quality filtering algorithms
that are powerful and controllable (frequencies in Hz, none
of this averaging / distance crap).

Based on mkfilter/mkshape/mkaverage/gencode/genplot:
  A. J. Fisher
  fisher@minster.york.ac.uk

@endnode

@node usage "cha_filter.guide/Usage"

cha_filter FROM/A,TO/A,RATE/K,VOLUME/K,BW=BUTTERWORTH/S,
           CH=CHEBYSHEV/S,BE=BESSEL/S,RES=RESONATOR/S,
           HP=HIGHPASS/S,LP=LOWPASS/S,BP=BANDPASS/S,
           BS=BANDSTOP/S,AP=ALLPASS/S,NOTCH/S,
           BLT=BILINEAR/S,MZT=MATCHEDZ/S,O=ORDER/K,
           R=RIPPLE/K,F=FREQUENCY/K,LF=LOWFREQUENCY/K,
           HF=HIGHFREQUENCY/K,Q=QFACTOR/K

Looks complicated, but is in fact quite logical.  Check the
@{" usage map " link usage_map} if you are not convinced.

general:

FROM        - the source sample number (1..1V)
TO          - the destination sample number (1..1V)
RATE        - the sample rate (if not specified then the
              rate is taken from the default pitch of the
              source sample (default C-3 = 16574 Hz))
VOLUME      - volume factor (default 1.0, change this if the
              output is too loud or too quiet)

filters designed in the s-plane:

BUTTERWORTH - "normal" filter (flat pass band)
CHEBYSHEV   - steeper frequency cutoff slope but ripples in
              the pass band (see RIPPLE)
BESSEL      - linear phase response but shallower frequency
              cutoff slope

s-plane -> z-plane conversion methods:

BILINEAR    - bilinear transform, generally preferred as the
              frequency response is sharper
MATCHEDZ    - matched z-transform, preserves the phase
              response so use this for Bessel filters, but
              aliasing can distort the frequency response

s-plane filter shapes:

HIGHPASS    - pass frequencies above FREQUENCY but not below
LOWPASS     - pass frequencies below FREQUENCY but not above
BANDSTOP    - pass frequencies below LOWFREQUENCY or above
              HIGHFREQUENCY but not inbetween
BANDPASS    - pass frequencies between LOWFREQUENCY and
              HIGHFREQUENCY but not outside

s-plane parameters:

FREQUENCY       - center frequency in Hz
LOWFREQUENCY    - lower frequency in Hz
HIGHFREQUENCY   - higher frequency in Hz
ORDER       - the order of the filter (1..16) (the frequency
              response cutoff slope is 6 * order dB/octave)
RIPPLE      - specifies Chebyshev passband ripple in dB
              (must be less than 0.0)

other filter types:

RESONATOR   - simple filter

resonator filter shapes:

BANDPASS    - pass frequencies near FREQUENCY
ALLPASS     - change phase response near FREQUENCY
NOTCH       - eliminate FREQUENCY

resonator parameters:

FREQUENCY   - center frequency in Hz
QFACTOR     - filter Q-factor (the higher the Q-factor the
              more "local" to the frequency the effect is)

@endnode

@node usage_map "cha_filter.guide/Usage Map"

Here is how the command line interface parameters are
connected:

                      /-- highpass --\\
     bessel --\\      /                \\
               \\    /---- lowpass  ----\\    /-- bilinear --\\
butterworth ----}--{                    }--{                \\
               /    \\---- bandstop ----/    \\-- matchedz ----\\
  chebyshev --/      \\                /                       \\
                      \\-- bandpass --/      /-- bandpass ------}--
                                           /                  /
  resonator ------------------------------{---- allpass  ----/
                                           \\                /
                                            \\-- notch    --/

Notes:

- s-plane filters need ORDER (1..16)
- Chebyshev filters need RIPPLE (< 0.0 dB)
- s-plane bandpass filters need LOW/HIGHFREQUENCY, all other
  filters need FREQUENCY (>= 0.0 Hz)
- resonators need QFACTOR (> 0.0)

@endnode

@node examples "cha_filter/Examples"

As the CLI is a bit awkward, I thought I'd give lots of
examples of usage.  First is the long version, then the
short version of the same command.  All of the examples
are with a sample rate of 16574 Hz (C-3).


cha_filter from 1 to 2 butterworth bilinear lowpass frequency 250 order 4
cha_filter 1 2 bw blt lp f 250 o 4
    - simple lowpass filter

cha_filter from 1 to 2 butterworth bilinear highpass frequency 800 order 4
cha_filter 1 2 bw blt hp f 800 o 4
    - simple highpass filter

cha_filter from 1 to 2 butterworth bilinear bandpass lowfrequency 250 highfrequency 800 order 3
cha_filter 1 2 bw blt bp lf 250 hf 800 o 3
    - simple bandpass filter, (for these frequencies and
      rate the highest stable order is 3)

cha_filter from 1 to 2 chebyshev bilinear highpass frequency 4000 order 12 ripple -6
cha_filter 1 2 ch blt hp f 4000 o 12 r -6
    - extreme highpass filter, Chebyshev gives sharper cutoff

cha_filter from 1 to 2 bessel matchedz lowpass frequency 500 order 1
cha_filter 1 2 be mzt lp f 500 o 1
    - gentle lowpass filter (takes the edge off the treble)

cha_filter from 1 to 2 resonator bandpass frequency 300 qfactor 9 volume 0.5
cha_filter 1 2 res bp f 300 q 9 v 0.5
    - boost the bass, reducing the output volume to avoid
      distortion

cha_filter from 1 to 2 resonator bandpass frequency 600 qfactor 100 volume 2
cha_filter 1 2 res bp f 600 q 100 v 2
    - add (quite a lot of) resonance, increasing volume to
      use the full range of the output sample

cha_filter from 2 to 3 resonator notch frequency 600 qfactor 8 volume 4
cha_filter 2 3 res notch f 600 q 8 v 4
    - attempt to remove the added resonance

cha_filter from 1 to 2 resonator allpass frequency 600 qfactor 10
cha_filter 1 2 res ap f 400 q 100
    - allpass filter (note: although all frequencies are
      passed equally in the long term, the ear can detect
      short term changes, so it will not sound the same.
      The previous version of this guide said incorrectly
      that it would sound the same - there is in fact a
      "metallic ring".)

@endnode

@node bugs "cha_filter.guide/Bugs"

- s-plane filters with high ORDER can be unstable
    + use a lower ORDER and filter twice
    + there is a possible fix for this bug, but that
      requires a near rewrite of the filtering code (so that
      will wait until the next version, if ever)

- resonators with low QFACTOR are at the wrong frequency
    + use a higher QFACTOR
    + I will investigate this bug and hopefully fix it

@endnode

